Airline On-Time Performance Data¶

by João Victor Moreira de Figueiredo¶

Introduction¶

Reporting carriers are required to (or voluntarily) report on-time data for flights they operate: on-time arrival and departure data for non-stop domestic flights by month and year, by carrier and by origin and destination airport. Includes scheduled and actual departure and arrival times, canceled and diverted flights, taxi-out and taxi-in times, causes of delay and cancellation, air time, and non-stop distance.

This project explore twelve months of data, starting at May 2019 to April 2020 totaling approximately 7 million flights.

1. Load the dataset¶

Access this link to download the files that be scope of this project.

After download files, follow the next steps:

  1. Create a folder named 'files' in root project
  2. Inside files, create a folder named 'data'
  3. Copy the twelve zip files inside the 'data' folder
  4. The script bellow will descompress and rename the csv files

Obs: The script will take two minutes approximately to descompress all files

In [2]:
import zipfile
import os
import time
import glob

if os.path.exists('files/data/260700039_T_ONTIME_REPORTING11.csv'):
    pass
else:
    dir_files = os.listdir('files/data/')
    count_files = 0
    listfiles = []
    
    for i in dir_files:
        with zipfile.ZipFile('files/data/'+i, mode='r') as myzip:
            listfiles.append(zipfile.ZipFile.namelist(myzip)[0])
            myzip.extractall(path='files/data/')
            current_name = listfiles[count_files]
            new_name = listfiles[count_files].split('.')[0]+str(count_files)+'.csv'
        
            if os.path.exists('files/data/'+current_name):
                os.renames('files/data/'+current_name, 'files/'+new_name)
        
            count_files+=1

airports = 'https://www.transtats.bts.gov/Download_Lookup.asp?Lookup=L_AIRPORT'
airp_file = airports.split('=')[-1]+'.csv'

cancellation_desc = 'https://www.transtats.bts.gov/Download_Lookup.asp?Lookup=L_CANCELLATION'
canc_file = cancellation_desc.split('=')[-1]+'.csv'
In [6]:
import requests

if os.path.exists('files/supplementary_data'):
    pass
else:
    os.mkdir('files/supplementary_data')

if requests.get('https://www.transtats.bts.gov/').status_code == 200:
    with open('files/supplementary_data/'+week_days_file, mode='wb') as file:
        file.write(requests.get(week_days).content)

    with open('files/supplementary_data/'+carr_file, mode='wb') as file:
        file.write(requests.get(carriers).content)
    
    with open('files/supplementary_data/'+airp_file, mode='wb') as file:
        file.write(requests.get(airports).content)
    
    with open('files/supplementary_data/'+canc_file, mode='wb') as file:
        file.write(requests.get(cancellation_desc).content)
else:
    pass

2. Assess the dataframe¶

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset is composed by 35 columns and more of 7 millions of entries.

Some issues must be observed, like:

  • Strange column named 'Unnamed: 29'
  • Multiple NaN values
  • ORIGIN_DESC and DEST_DESC are multiple variables in the same column
  • Separe data in dataframes by: cancelled_flights, delayed_fligths and normal_flights (not cancelled and not delayed flights)
  • ORIGIN_DESC and DEST_DESC fields cannot be null

Get the reason of flight delays with melting specific columns

Obs: Not all delays in DEP_DELAY and ARR_DELAY have a reported reason. The focus here is to investigate the time and reason for delays in the 'CARRIER_DELAY', 'WEATHER_DELAY', 'NAS_DELAY', 'SECURITY_DELAY' and 'LATE_AIRCRAFT_DELAY'

In [32]:
columns = ['YEAR', 'MONTH', 'DAY_OF_MONTH', 'DAY_OF_WEEK', 'WEEK_DAY_NAME',
       'OP_CARRIER_FL_NUM', 'CARRIER_NAME','DISTANCE','DEP_DELAY', 'ARR_DELAY']

# TOTAL_DELAY_REASON in minutes
delay_reason = pd.melt(df_delayed, id_vars=columns,
                       value_vars=['CARRIER_DELAY','WEATHER_DELAY','NAS_DELAY',
                                   'SECURITY_DELAY','LATE_AIRCRAFT_DELAY'],
                       var_name='DELAY_REASON', value_name='TOTAL_DELAY_REASON')

Some outliers above 3000 miles. In the graph on the right, these outliers are explored in more detail and in the graph above, a log scale was applied to normalize the distribution. There is a spike in flights within outliers to locations between 3250 and 3500 miles and 3750 and 4000 miles.

Interestingly looking at these two charts and that there was a spike in cancellation for security and operator reasons starting in the same period (Feb 2020), two days after a declaration of outbreak of COVID-19 to be a Public Health Emergency of International Concern link.

Many flights canceled by the "Carrier" themselves, but the overwhelming majority for security reasons, which were rarely used in the months before Feb 2020.
